1
00:01:40,480 --> 00:01:41,720
In order to show you how

2
00:01:41,800 --> 00:01:44,280
a big symphony
orchestra is put together,

3
00:01:44,360 --> 00:01:47,440
Benjamin Britten
has written a big piece of music,

4
00:01:47,520 --> 00:01:49,280
which is made up
of smaller pieces

5
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:52,360
that show you all
the separate parts of the orchestra.

6
00:01:52,440 --> 00:01:55,200
These smaller pieces
are called variations,

7
00:01:55,280 --> 00:01:58,800
which means different ways
of playing the same tune.

8
00:01:58,920 --> 00:02:02,120
First of all,
he lets us hear the tune or the theme,

9
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:03,320
which is a beautiful melody

10
00:02:03,400 --> 00:02:06,760
by the much older
British composer Henry Purcell.

11
00:02:06,840 --> 00:02:11,280
Here is Purcell's theme
played by the whole orchestra together.

12
00:02:40,440 --> 00:02:44,400
Now, Mr. Britten lets you hear the four
different families of the orchestra

13
00:02:44,480 --> 00:02:47,400
playing the same Purcell theme
in different ways.

14
00:02:47,480 --> 00:02:49,280
First, we hear
the woodwind family.

15
00:02:49,360 --> 00:02:53,000
The flutes, the oboes,
the clarinets and the bassoons.

16
00:03:15,240 --> 00:03:17,160
Here comes the brass family.

17
00:03:17,240 --> 00:03:20,520
The trumpets, the horns,
the trombones and the tubas.

18
00:03:26,600 --> 00:03:27,960
One to four.

19
00:03:39,320 --> 00:03:43,360
Now, Mr. Britten arranges the Purcell theme
for the string family.

20
00:03:43,440 --> 00:03:44,480
I'm sick of this rain.

21
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:48,960
The violins, the violas, the
cellos and the double basses.

22
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:51,400
And of course, the harp.

23
00:04:12,320 --> 00:04:14,680
And finally
the percussion family,

24
00:04:14,760 --> 00:04:18,040
all those drums and gongs
and things you hit.

25
00:04:21,760 --> 00:04:24,200
After this, you will
hear the theme by Purcell

26
00:04:24,280 --> 00:04:28,200
played once more in its original
form by all four families together.

27
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:30,560
That is, the whole orchestra.

28
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:56,480
This is
the island of New Penzance.

29
00:04:57,840 --> 00:04:59,720
16 miles long.

30
00:05:00,880 --> 00:05:03,840
Forested with
old-growth pine and maple.

31
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,600
Criss-crossed by
shallow tidal creeks.

32
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:11,080
Chickchaw territory.

33
00:05:11,640 --> 00:05:12,640
There are no
paved roads, but...

34
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:15,920
Here comes Jed with the mail.

35
00:05:16,040 --> 00:05:20,040
But instead many miles of intersecting
footpaths and dirt trails,

36
00:05:20,120 --> 00:05:23,160
and a ferry that
runs twice daily from Stone Cove.

37
00:05:24,120 --> 00:05:27,480
The year is 1965.

38
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:31,520
We are on the far edge
of Black Beacon Sound,

39
00:05:31,600 --> 00:05:34,240
famous for the ferocious
and well-documented storm,

40
00:05:34,320 --> 00:05:37,560
which will strike from the
east on the 5th of September.

41
00:05:38,320 --> 00:05:40,800
In three days' time.

42
00:05:56,960 --> 00:05:58,160
Morning, Gadge.

43
00:05:58,240 --> 00:05:59,520
Morning, sir.

44
00:06:08,320 --> 00:06:10,480
Deluca, latrine inspection.

45
00:06:19,160 --> 00:06:20,520
Good.

46
00:06:22,640 --> 00:06:24,840
Roosevelt,
how's that lanyard coming?

47
00:06:25,840 --> 00:06:27,000
Horrible.

48
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:32,800
Skotak,
what's all this lumber for?

49
00:06:32,880 --> 00:06:34,200
We're building a tree house.

50
00:06:34,280 --> 00:06:35,640
- Where?
- Right here.

51
00:06:38,320 --> 00:06:41,560
That's not a safe altitude.
Why is it up so high?

52
00:06:41,640 --> 00:06:43,720
If someone falls from there,
that's a guaranteed death.

53
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:44,920
Well, where would
you have built it?

54
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:47,160
Lower.

55
00:06:53,160 --> 00:06:54,800
Nickleby? What are you doing?

56
00:06:54,880 --> 00:06:56,520
Pest control.
Burning some ants.

57
00:06:56,600 --> 00:06:58,240
Spot check.

58
00:07:00,280 --> 00:07:02,000
Your socks are down,
your shirt tails are untucked,

59
00:07:02,080 --> 00:07:03,480
your trousers are
not properly pressed.

60
00:07:03,560 --> 00:07:06,000
You are reported for
a uniform violation.

61
00:07:09,040 --> 00:07:10,240
How many rockets
you up to, Panagle?

62
00:07:10,320 --> 00:07:11,360
Sixteen and a half, sir.

63
00:07:11,440 --> 00:07:12,760
Is that enough
for the Hullabaloo?

64
00:07:12,840 --> 00:07:15,400
Izod, go fetch another pint of
gunpowder from the armory shed.

65
00:07:15,480 --> 00:07:16,840
Redford! Halt! I saw that!

66
00:07:18,480 --> 00:07:19,960
- How fast were you just going?
- Safety test, sir.

67
00:07:20,040 --> 00:07:21,080
Come again?

68
00:07:21,160 --> 00:07:22,400
The vehicle
appears to be in good working order,

69
00:07:22,520 --> 00:07:23,600
I'm just checking if...

70
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:25,080
Reckless cycling.
Second warning.

71
00:07:25,160 --> 00:07:26,960
Next time,
I take away the keys.

72
00:07:28,960 --> 00:07:30,640
Morning, Chef.

73
00:07:40,920 --> 00:07:41,800
Clear!

74
00:07:53,720 --> 00:07:55,840
Who's missing?

75
00:07:55,920 --> 00:07:57,880
- Who's missing?
- Shakusky.

76
00:07:57,960 --> 00:08:01,080
- Shakusky.
- Shakusky.

77
00:08:01,160 --> 00:08:02,720
Shakusky! Breakfast!

78
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:11,320
Shakusky, you in there?

79
00:08:12,720 --> 00:08:14,160
Sam?

80
00:08:17,400 --> 00:08:18,800
It's zipped from the inside.

81
00:08:44,520 --> 00:08:46,840
Jiminy Cricket,
he flew the coop.

82
00:09:06,320 --> 00:09:08,160
Hello, this is
Captain Sharp, over.

83
00:09:08,240 --> 00:09:11,760
Captain Sharp, this is Randall
Ward over at Camp Ivanhoe. Over.

84
00:09:11,840 --> 00:09:13,880
Morning, Randy.
What can I do for you? Over.

85
00:09:13,960 --> 00:09:18,520
I'm not sure exactly.
I've got an escaped Khaki Scout. Over.

86
00:09:20,200 --> 00:09:21,640
What does that mean? Over.

87
00:09:21,720 --> 00:09:23,320
One of my boys
seems to have stolen

88
00:09:23,400 --> 00:09:25,320
a miniature canoe and
some fishing tackle,

89
00:09:25,400 --> 00:09:28,360
10 pounds of sundries,
two bedrolls, plus an air rifle.

90
00:09:28,440 --> 00:09:30,480
And disappeared. Over.

91
00:09:30,560 --> 00:09:31,920
Any idea why? Over.

92
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:35,160
No. He left me
a letter of resignation. Over.

93
00:09:35,240 --> 00:09:36,440
Dear Scout Master Ward,

94
00:09:36,520 --> 00:09:39,240
I am very sad to inform you
I can no longer be involved

95
00:09:39,320 --> 00:09:41,160
with the Khaki
Scouts of North America.

96
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:43,440
The rest of the troop
will probably be glad to hear this.

97
00:09:43,520 --> 00:09:44,560
It is not your fault.

98
00:09:44,640 --> 00:09:46,200
Best wishes, Sam Shakusky.

99
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,360
Well, I guess we better
notify his folks. Over.

100
00:09:51,440 --> 00:09:53,680
Okay. Over and out.

101
00:10:08,920 --> 00:10:09,960
Hello, Diane.

102
00:10:10,040 --> 00:10:12,720
Becky, I have your
person-to-person from Chesterfield

103
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:13,960
Hold the line, please.

104
00:10:15,760 --> 00:10:16,800
Hello?

105
00:10:16,880 --> 00:10:18,640
Hello, sir.
This is Captain Sharp.

106
00:10:18,720 --> 00:10:22,040
Yes, sir. I received your
message. Thank you very much.

107
00:10:22,120 --> 00:10:25,560
In fact, we've come to
a decision, as a family,

108
00:10:25,640 --> 00:10:29,800
because this is only the most recent
incident involving Sam's troubles,

109
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:33,000
and it's just not
fair to the others, so, unfortunately,

110
00:10:33,080 --> 00:10:36,440
we can't invite him
back at this time.

111
00:10:38,880 --> 00:10:42,600
There's no cause
for alarm, sir. We'll find him.

112
00:10:42,680 --> 00:10:45,400
We're simply notifying you
as a matter of protocol and so on.

113
00:10:45,720 --> 00:10:48,760
I understand that. I'm notifying
you of the situation on my end.

114
00:10:49,800 --> 00:10:52,760
I'm confused by
that statement. You can't invite him back?

115
00:10:53,360 --> 00:10:56,720
I'm afraid not.
He's a good boy. He's got a good heart.

116
00:10:56,800 --> 00:10:59,520
But it's just not fair
to the others, you see?

117
00:11:00,360 --> 00:11:02,440
He's emotionally disturbed.

118
00:11:06,120 --> 00:11:07,800
Am I speaking
with Sam's father?

119
00:11:09,680 --> 00:11:11,560
No, sir.

120
00:11:11,640 --> 00:11:13,840
Sam's parents passed away
a number of years ago.

121
00:11:13,920 --> 00:11:16,960
We're Mr. and
Mrs. Billingsley. We're foster parents.

122
00:11:17,520 --> 00:11:20,120
Sam's been with
us since last June.

123
00:11:20,240 --> 00:11:23,040
Excuse me, sir.
This is Scout Master Ward speaking.

124
00:11:23,120 --> 00:11:24,880
Are you implying
that Sam is an orphan?

125
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:27,520
Well, it's a known fact.
Of course he is.

126
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:29,720
Well, why the hell
doesn't it say so in the register?

127
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:30,880
Excuse my language.

128
00:11:31,800 --> 00:11:33,200
I don't know. What register?

129
00:11:35,880 --> 00:11:37,920
We sent him a letter.
It should reach you presently.

130
00:11:39,320 --> 00:11:42,080
Mr. Billingsley,
I've got an escaped Khaki Scout.

131
00:11:42,160 --> 00:11:44,440
We are notifying you
as a matter of protocol.

132
00:11:44,520 --> 00:11:47,720
You say you can't invite him back?
You say that he's an orphan?

133
00:11:48,360 --> 00:11:50,040
I don't understand
how that works.

134
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:52,640
What am I supposed
to do with him?

135
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:56,360
That's up to social services.
They'll be in touch with you.

136
00:11:56,440 --> 00:11:59,200
They'll look after Sam.
Good luck to you.

137
00:12:07,600 --> 00:12:08,720
You have your orders.

138
00:12:08,800 --> 00:12:10,760
Use the orienteering
and path-finding skills

139
00:12:10,840 --> 00:12:12,400
that you've been
practicing all summer.

140
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:15,360
Let's find our man,
bring him safely back to camp.

141
00:12:15,440 --> 00:12:17,640
Remember, this isn't
just a search party,

142
00:12:17,720 --> 00:12:19,840
it's a chance to do
some first class Scouting.

143
00:12:19,920 --> 00:12:22,080
Any questions?

144
00:12:22,160 --> 00:12:23,280
Lazy-Eye?

145
00:12:23,360 --> 00:12:24,960
What's your real job, sir?

146
00:12:25,040 --> 00:12:26,840
- I'm a math teacher. Why?
- What grade?

147
00:12:26,920 --> 00:12:28,600
- Eighth.
- You need a PhD for that?

148
00:12:28,680 --> 00:12:30,000
Lazy-Eye, no,
but you know what,

149
00:12:30,120 --> 00:12:32,640
we're actually in the middle of something
here, in case you didn't notice.

150
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:34,840
One of our Scouts is missing
and that's a crisis.

151
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:35,960
Anybody else? Redford?

152
00:12:36,080 --> 00:12:37,120
What if he resists?

153
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:38,280
- Who?
- Shakusky.

154
00:12:38,360 --> 00:12:39,400
Are we allowed to
use force on him?

155
00:12:39,480 --> 00:12:43,640
No, you're not.
This is a non-violent, rescue operation.

156
00:12:43,720 --> 00:12:47,080
Your mission is to find him,
not to hurt him under any circumstances.

157
00:12:47,160 --> 00:12:49,040
Am I making myself understood?

158
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:50,920
- Yes.
- Good.

159
00:12:52,440 --> 00:12:55,040
I'm going to change my answer,
in fact, this is my real job.

160
00:12:55,160 --> 00:12:58,720
Scout Master Troop 55.
I'm a math teacher on the side.

161
00:12:59,800 --> 00:13:01,520
Be leery out there. Okay?

162
00:13:01,600 --> 00:13:03,040
Now let's get started.
Who's got Snoopy?

163
00:13:03,120 --> 00:13:04,440
Right here.

164
00:13:04,960 --> 00:13:06,840
Give him the scent.

165
00:13:10,640 --> 00:13:12,680
I heard he ran away
because his family died.

166
00:13:13,040 --> 00:13:15,040
I heard he
never had any family in the first place.

167
00:13:15,120 --> 00:13:16,440
That's probably why he's crazy.

168
00:13:16,520 --> 00:13:17,640
I'll tell you one thing,

169
00:13:17,720 --> 00:13:20,480
if we find him, I'm not going to be the
one who forgot to bring a weapon.

170
00:13:20,560 --> 00:13:22,520
Me, neither.

171
00:14:10,680 --> 00:14:13,440
Camp Ivanhoe, that's all the way
across the other side of the island.

172
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:14,800
You really think
a 12-year-old boy

173
00:14:14,880 --> 00:14:16,800
could row this far
in a miniature canoe?

174
00:14:16,880 --> 00:14:17,920
Most likely not.

175
00:14:18,040 --> 00:14:19,480
It is possible, Counselor.

176
00:14:19,560 --> 00:14:21,760
I disagree, Counselor.
It would take him three days, at least.

177
00:14:21,840 --> 00:14:23,280
I don't think so.
Two days, maximum.

178
00:14:23,360 --> 00:14:25,600
- Well, I'm not going to argue about it.
- Be that as it may,

179
00:14:25,720 --> 00:14:27,640
- will you let me know if you see anything unusual?
- Yup.

180
00:15:36,440 --> 00:15:39,320
Scout Master's log,
September 2nd.

181
00:15:39,400 --> 00:15:41,800
First day of search
party for Sam Shakusky

182
00:15:42,200 --> 00:15:43,480
Morale is extremely low,

183
00:15:43,560 --> 00:15:44,600
in part, I suppose,

184
00:15:44,680 --> 00:15:46,960
because Sam is
the least popular Scout in the troop.

185
00:15:47,960 --> 00:15:49,400
By a significant margin.

186
00:15:51,040 --> 00:15:53,760
I'm confused and I'm worried.

187
00:15:55,360 --> 00:15:57,760
Please let us
find him tomorrow.

188
00:15:57,840 --> 00:16:01,160
Please don't let
him fall off a cliff,

189
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:03,440
or drown in the goddamn
lake or something.

190
00:16:03,520 --> 00:16:05,120
A terrible day at Camp Ivanhoe.

191
00:16:08,320 --> 00:16:09,960
Let's hope tomorrow's better.

192
00:17:36,680 --> 00:17:38,920
One Year earlier

193
00:19:07,720 --> 00:19:08,920
What kind of bird are you?

194
00:19:09,920 --> 00:19:12,160
I'm a sparrow, she's a dove...

195
00:19:12,240 --> 00:19:16,400
No. I said,
what kind of bird are you?

196
00:19:19,600 --> 00:19:20,840
I'm a raven.

197
00:19:22,200 --> 00:19:23,400
Boys aren't allowed in here.

198
00:19:24,960 --> 00:19:26,120
I'll be leaving soon.

199
00:19:29,200 --> 00:19:30,440
What happened to your hand?

200
00:19:32,520 --> 00:19:34,240
I got hit in the mirror.

201
00:19:34,320 --> 00:19:36,040
Really, how did that happen?

202
00:19:37,320 --> 00:19:39,240
I lost my temper at myself.

203
00:19:42,720 --> 00:19:43,800
What's your name?

204
00:19:43,880 --> 00:19:45,120
Sam. What's yours?

205
00:19:45,600 --> 00:19:46,960
I'm Suzy.

206
00:19:49,640 --> 00:19:51,040
It's not polite to stare.

207
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:53,720
- Birds, ready?
- Who are you?

208
00:19:53,800 --> 00:19:55,360
Where did you come from?
Go back to your seat.

209
00:20:01,520 --> 00:20:03,200
He likes you.

210
00:20:36,560 --> 00:20:37,720
Were you followed?

211
00:20:40,200 --> 00:20:41,680
- I doubt it.
- Good.

212
00:20:44,240 --> 00:20:45,480
Is that a cat in there?

213
00:20:53,720 --> 00:20:55,920
Can you read a map?

214
00:20:56,320 --> 00:20:58,520
I do cartography.

215
00:20:58,600 --> 00:21:00,720
I feel we should
go halfway today, and halfway tomorrow

216
00:21:00,800 --> 00:21:02,200
since you're a less
experienced hiker,

217
00:21:02,280 --> 00:21:04,320
and you're wearing
Sunday school shoes.

218
00:21:04,400 --> 00:21:05,440
They're not really
Sunday school shoes.

219
00:21:05,520 --> 00:21:06,560
Here.

220
00:21:06,640 --> 00:21:07,680
Oh, thank you.

221
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:11,720
Here's where we are right now.

222
00:21:11,800 --> 00:21:13,920
I'd like to pitch
camp here by 1600,

223
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:15,840
which means 4:00.
How does that sound?

224
00:21:15,920 --> 00:21:17,800
- Fine.
- You want some beef jerky?

225
00:21:17,920 --> 00:21:19,320
- Okay.
- Let's go.

226
00:21:32,120 --> 00:21:33,480
Are you thirsty?

227
00:21:33,560 --> 00:21:34,920
No, thank you.

228
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:37,080
Well, if your throat
gets parched,

229
00:21:37,160 --> 00:21:38,960
stick a pebble in your
mouth and suck on it.

230
00:21:39,040 --> 00:21:40,920
You can quench your thirst
with the spit, supposedly.

231
00:21:43,160 --> 00:21:46,360
Sometimes I stick leaves on my
hair. It helps cool your head down.

232
00:21:46,440 --> 00:21:47,480
That's a good idea.

233
00:21:47,560 --> 00:21:49,880
It might also help if
you didn't wear a fur hat.

234
00:21:49,960 --> 00:21:51,920
Yeah. True.

235
00:21:53,200 --> 00:21:56,480
You can go ahead. Be careful.

236
00:22:07,560 --> 00:22:09,320
Here's a trick,
throw pine needles in the air

237
00:22:09,400 --> 00:22:11,320
and you can see
which direction the wind is blowing.

238
00:22:15,560 --> 00:22:16,920
Which Way?

239
00:22:19,680 --> 00:22:20,800
I guess it
doesn't really matter,

240
00:22:20,880 --> 00:22:22,200
just as long as we
cover our tracks.

241
00:22:33,640 --> 00:22:35,640
You smell like perfume.

242
00:22:35,720 --> 00:22:37,120
Oh, it's my mother's.

243
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:51,880
I brought water, too.

244
00:22:55,200 --> 00:22:56,840
- You wait here.
- Okay.

245
00:22:58,080 --> 00:22:59,480
Be right back.

246
00:23:02,640 --> 00:23:03,840
Watch your head!

247
00:23:13,880 --> 00:23:15,240
Where the hell is it?

248
00:23:22,320 --> 00:23:23,600
Found it!

249
00:23:34,360 --> 00:23:35,480
It's ready.

250
00:23:36,440 --> 00:23:38,920
He knows someone's
watching him.

251
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:42,560
I agree. Wait.
Why do you say that?

252
00:23:43,920 --> 00:23:46,760
I don't know,
I just think he can feel us.

253
00:23:52,160 --> 00:23:53,680
Follow me.

254
00:24:21,080 --> 00:24:22,680
How strong of
a swimmer are you?

255
00:24:22,760 --> 00:24:25,520
Pretty good. I broke our school
record for the backstroke.

256
00:24:25,600 --> 00:24:29,160
Okay. Well, I'm not that strong of a
swimmer, so I wear a life preserver.

257
00:24:35,040 --> 00:24:36,160
Watch out for turtles.

258
00:24:36,240 --> 00:24:38,760
They'll bite you
if you put your fingers down their mouths.

259
00:24:38,840 --> 00:24:40,400
Okay.

260
00:24:40,480 --> 00:24:42,200
Let me see if I
can catch this one.

261
00:24:45,040 --> 00:24:46,520
Feel something.

262
00:24:52,480 --> 00:24:53,800
Somebody wrote on him.

263
00:24:54,920 --> 00:24:56,800
The stick's moving.

264
00:24:56,880 --> 00:24:58,040
You got one!

265
00:24:59,320 --> 00:25:02,040
Fish on hook!
Reel him in, slowly.

266
00:25:15,720 --> 00:25:18,680
Very good.
You know a lot about camping, don't you?

267
00:25:19,520 --> 00:25:23,640
I'm a Khaki Scout. It's what I'm trained
for. Well, anyway, I used to be.

268
00:25:24,680 --> 00:25:28,120
Maybe we can feed your cat
the guts and eyeballs.

269
00:25:28,200 --> 00:25:29,880
Oh, that's okay.
He only eats kitten food.

270
00:25:31,240 --> 00:25:32,280
Oh.

271
00:25:32,960 --> 00:25:35,680
What else did you bring?
Maybe we can make an inventory.

272
00:25:36,520 --> 00:25:37,640
Okay.

273
00:25:48,120 --> 00:25:49,160
Go ahead.

274
00:25:49,480 --> 00:25:52,200
This is my record player.
It works with batteries.

275
00:25:52,280 --> 00:25:54,640
Well, actually,
it belongs to my little brother, Lionel.

276
00:25:54,720 --> 00:25:56,200
- I left him a note.
- Okay.

277
00:25:56,280 --> 00:25:58,160
- Do you like music?
- Yeah.

278
00:25:59,240 --> 00:26:01,200
This is my
favorite record album.

279
00:26:01,280 --> 00:26:03,280
My godmother gave it
to me for my birthday.

280
00:26:03,360 --> 00:26:05,120
She lives in France.

281
00:26:07,160 --> 00:26:10,520
These are my books.
I like stories with magic powers in them.

282
00:26:10,600 --> 00:26:13,040
Either in kingdoms on Earth
or on foreign planets.

283
00:26:13,120 --> 00:26:16,240
Usually, I prefer
a girl hero, but not always.

284
00:26:16,320 --> 00:26:18,440
I couldn't bring them all
because it got too heavy.

285
00:26:18,520 --> 00:26:19,640
You can borrow any you want.

286
00:26:19,720 --> 00:26:20,760
Thank you.

287
00:26:20,840 --> 00:26:25,720
I also brought
my lefty scissors because I'm left-handed,

288
00:26:25,800 --> 00:26:30,320
some rubber bands,
extra batteries, my toothbrush,

289
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:31,480
and my binoculars, as you know.

290
00:26:31,560 --> 00:26:32,600
Yeah.

291
00:26:32,680 --> 00:26:34,880
I forgot my comb.
But I'll use my fingers.

292
00:26:43,680 --> 00:26:47,560
Wait, these are all
library books.

293
00:26:47,640 --> 00:26:51,520
In my school, you're only
allowed to check out one at a time.

294
00:26:51,960 --> 00:26:54,840
Some of these are
going to be overdue.

295
00:26:56,720 --> 00:26:57,920
Do you steal?

296
00:27:00,520 --> 00:27:02,200
Why? You're not poor.

297
00:27:03,360 --> 00:27:07,080
I might turn some of them back in one day.
I haven't decided yet.

298
00:27:07,160 --> 00:27:10,720
I know it's bad. I think I just took
them to have a secret to keep.

299
00:27:10,800 --> 00:27:12,480
Anyway, for some reason,

300
00:27:12,560 --> 00:27:14,200
it makes me feel in
a better mood sometimes.

301
00:27:15,720 --> 00:27:17,400
Are you depressed?

302
00:27:19,160 --> 00:27:20,400
How come?

303
00:27:20,480 --> 00:27:22,760
Well, I can show you
an example, if you'd like,

304
00:27:24,280 --> 00:27:26,520
but it doesn't make
me feel very good.

305
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:30,920
Anyway, I found this
on top of our refrigerator.

306
00:27:32,280 --> 00:27:33,320
Does that mean you?

307
00:27:34,480 --> 00:27:35,840
I think so.

308
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:41,400
Are you laughing?

309
00:27:44,760 --> 00:27:45,800
It's not funny.

310
00:27:49,560 --> 00:27:52,080
You really know
how to make friends.

311
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:12,240
I'm sorry.

312
00:28:13,520 --> 00:28:15,360
Oh. It's okay.

313
00:28:15,720 --> 00:28:17,360
I'm on your side.

314
00:28:18,840 --> 00:28:20,160
I know.

315
00:28:25,200 --> 00:28:26,600
Thank you.

316
00:28:30,680 --> 00:28:33,120
Which one's the best?

317
00:28:33,200 --> 00:28:37,360
"His eyes downcast, his kingdom in
ruins, Mynar pressed his heavy paw"

318
00:28:37,440 --> 00:28:39,360
"through the rippling surface
of the cool shallows"

319
00:28:39,440 --> 00:28:41,080
"and down to its stone floor."

320
00:28:41,160 --> 00:28:44,240
"My people once were led
by a great and noble beast"

321
00:28:44,320 --> 00:28:47,520
"and I no longer
see his face in this reflection.'"

322
00:29:02,160 --> 00:29:05,400
"Meanwhile,
on the Plains of Tabitha, Francine rested."

323
00:29:05,480 --> 00:29:07,440
"There would be
another time for war."

324
00:29:10,240 --> 00:29:12,920
Suzy! Dinner! I'm not
going to say it again.

325
00:29:15,240 --> 00:29:16,720
Where's your sister?

326
00:29:16,800 --> 00:29:21,120
I don't know, but she borrowed my record
player for 10 days without asking.

327
00:29:21,200 --> 00:29:23,840
What does that mean?

328
00:29:23,920 --> 00:29:26,320
Dear Lionel, I need
to use your record player.

329
00:29:26,440 --> 00:29:29,960
I will give it back in 10 days or less.
Do not tell Mom. Or Dad.

330
00:29:30,040 --> 00:29:33,240
I will replace the batteries when I
return. Signed, Suzy Bishop.

331
00:29:36,160 --> 00:29:37,760
Walt! Where the hell are you?

332
00:29:37,840 --> 00:29:38,960
Right here!

333
00:29:39,040 --> 00:29:40,960
Why are you cursing at me?

334
00:29:41,040 --> 00:29:43,680
Does it concern you that
your daughter's just run away from home?

335
00:29:46,840 --> 00:29:48,120
That's a loaded question.

336
00:29:48,640 --> 00:29:49,960
Come down and read this.

337
00:29:50,640 --> 00:29:53,240
Scout Master Ward
confirms they've had no luck.

338
00:29:53,320 --> 00:29:54,360
They're going home for...

339
00:29:57,480 --> 00:29:58,520
Who's there?

340
00:30:03,560 --> 00:30:06,280
Good evening.
Sorry to startle you.

341
00:30:06,360 --> 00:30:08,880
What are you doing here?
Nobody called the police.

342
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:11,280
I know. I know.

343
00:30:11,360 --> 00:30:13,760
The search party's
not over yet. In other words...

344
00:30:13,840 --> 00:30:16,000
Suzy's missing, too!
Go find her.

345
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:21,240
The tropical cyclone,
which originated last week

346
00:30:21,320 --> 00:30:24,120
off the coast of
British Honduras, has intensified rapidly

347
00:30:24,240 --> 00:30:26,800
and is now designated
Hurricane Mabeline.

348
00:30:26,880 --> 00:30:28,600
Stay tuned for
further information

349
00:30:33,920 --> 00:30:38,480
How can we help her?
She's got so many problems.

350
00:30:39,160 --> 00:30:40,960
It's getting worse.

351
00:30:42,600 --> 00:30:44,240
Whose fault is it?

352
00:30:44,320 --> 00:30:45,440
I don't know.

353
00:30:46,200 --> 00:30:48,920
But just for the record
95% of all runaways

354
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:50,880
return home within
the first six hours.

355
00:30:51,440 --> 00:30:54,440
That doesn't do you
any good right now. It's just a statistic.

356
00:30:54,880 --> 00:30:57,320
But in all likelihood,
Suzy's probably hiding in the closet

357
00:30:57,400 --> 00:30:59,680
at her best friend's house
playing Chinese checkers

358
00:30:59,760 --> 00:31:02,080
at this very moment,
as we speak.

359
00:31:02,160 --> 00:31:04,360
She doesn't have any friends.

360
00:31:05,880 --> 00:31:07,240
How's Laura?

361
00:31:10,440 --> 00:31:11,800
"How's Laura?"

362
00:31:11,880 --> 00:31:13,440
Mrs. Bishop, I mean.

363
00:31:13,520 --> 00:31:16,080
I don't understand.

364
00:31:16,160 --> 00:31:17,520
Is she upset?

365
00:31:31,920 --> 00:31:33,280
There's a porcupine.

366
00:31:42,760 --> 00:31:47,320
She has a pen pal! It's very intimate.
They planned this together.

367
00:31:48,360 --> 00:31:51,600
Sam Shakusky.
That's my escaped Khaki Scout.

368
00:31:51,680 --> 00:31:52,760
His family died.

369
00:31:52,840 --> 00:31:54,840
Holy Christ,
what am I looking at?

370
00:31:54,920 --> 00:31:58,240
He does watercolors.
Mostly landscapes, but a few nudes.

371
00:31:58,320 --> 00:31:59,360
She sit for this?

372
00:31:59,440 --> 00:32:00,480
What's he say?

373
00:32:03,040 --> 00:32:05,240
Dear Suzy,
you have a superb voice.

374
00:32:05,320 --> 00:32:07,600
You were my favorite animal
in the program, by far.

375
00:32:07,680 --> 00:32:09,040
Please find enclosed...

376
00:32:09,120 --> 00:32:10,760
Dear Sam, thank you very much.

377
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:13,600
I got replaced as the raven
because I yelled at Mrs. Lynn.

378
00:32:13,680 --> 00:32:15,440
After that,
I was only a blue jay, but...

379
00:32:15,520 --> 00:32:18,320
Dear Suzy, I'm sorry
that your brothers are so selfish.

380
00:32:18,400 --> 00:32:19,760
Maybe they will grow out of it.

381
00:32:19,880 --> 00:32:22,360
Sometimes people do things
without knowing the reasons for...

382
00:32:22,440 --> 00:32:24,200
Dear Sam, you are
an excellent painter,

383
00:32:24,280 --> 00:32:25,960
especially trees
and telephone poles.

384
00:32:26,040 --> 00:32:29,120
Is the girl in the water supposed to be
me? My favorite color is...

385
00:32:29,200 --> 00:32:32,920
Dear Suzy, I accidentally built a
fire while I was sleepwalking.

386
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:36,080
I have no memory of this,
but my foster parents think I am lying.

387
00:32:36,200 --> 00:32:37,200
Unfortunately, it is...

388
00:32:37,320 --> 00:32:39,280
Dear Sam, I am in trouble again

389
00:32:39,360 --> 00:32:40,880
because I threw a rock
through the window.

390
00:32:40,960 --> 00:32:43,360
My mother still has
glass in her hair. Also...

391
00:32:43,440 --> 00:32:45,920
Dear Suzy, I have been
trying very hard to make friends,

392
00:32:46,040 --> 00:32:48,480
but I feel people do
not like my personality.

393
00:32:48,560 --> 00:32:50,400
In fact, I can understand
why they might not...

394
00:32:50,480 --> 00:32:52,360
Dear Sam,
now I am getting suspended

395
00:32:52,440 --> 00:32:53,960
because I got in
a fight with Molly.

396
00:32:54,040 --> 00:32:57,040
She says I go berserk.
Our principal is against me. Why do some...

397
00:32:57,120 --> 00:32:59,440
Dear Suzy, I know your parents
hurt' your feelings,

398
00:32:59,520 --> 00:33:02,520
but they still love you.
That is more important. If they...

399
00:33:02,600 --> 00:33:04,240
Dear Sam, I do think you should

400
00:33:04,320 --> 00:33:05,480
think of their faces every day,

401
00:33:05,600 --> 00:33:07,040
even if it makes you sad.

402
00:33:07,120 --> 00:33:08,560
It is too bad they
did not leave you

403
00:33:08,640 --> 00:33:10,560
more pictures of themselves.
Can you...

404
00:33:10,640 --> 00:33:12,560
Dear Suzy, here is my plan.

405
00:33:12,640 --> 00:33:14,640
Dear Sam, my answer is yes.

406
00:33:14,720 --> 00:33:16,120
Dear Suzy, when?

407
00:33:16,200 --> 00:33:17,800
Dear Sam, where?

408
00:33:17,880 --> 00:33:21,360
Dear Suzy,
walk 400 yards due north from your house

409
00:33:21,440 --> 00:33:23,960
to the dirt path
which has not got any name on it.

410
00:33:24,040 --> 00:33:27,920
Turn right and follow to the
end. I will meet you in the meadow.

411
00:33:35,680 --> 00:33:37,960
Gee whiz, what do you
suppose happened to him?

412
00:33:38,040 --> 00:33:41,440
I'm not sure.
I think he went searching in the dark.

413
00:33:41,520 --> 00:33:44,480
She stole the batteries
out of my flashlight.

414
00:33:44,560 --> 00:33:47,120
Stole the batteries
out of the flashlight...

415
00:33:49,280 --> 00:33:50,520
I think he's onto us.

416
00:33:50,600 --> 00:33:51,800
Of course he is.

417
00:33:51,880 --> 00:33:52,360
Of course he is?

418
00:33:53,120 --> 00:33:54,200
Of course he is.

419
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:58,240
Then why aren't we
worried about that?

420
00:33:58,320 --> 00:33:59,920
I am.

421
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:01,640
Well, I didn't know.

422
00:34:01,720 --> 00:34:05,080
Or, anyway,
I thought maybe I was wrong.

423
00:34:05,160 --> 00:34:06,200
Did you hit him?

424
00:34:06,280 --> 00:34:07,400
No. He fell in a ditch.

425
00:34:07,480 --> 00:34:12,120
Hey! Cat food!
I think it's a clue.

426
00:34:16,560 --> 00:34:17,920
That's her.

427
00:34:19,560 --> 00:34:21,240
Where's he going?

428
00:34:22,040 --> 00:34:23,480
I don't know.

429
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:26,680
All right,
we know they're together.

430
00:34:26,760 --> 00:34:28,960
We know they're within
a certain radius of this spot.

431
00:34:29,040 --> 00:34:31,280
I'm declaring a case
with the county right now.

432
00:34:31,360 --> 00:34:34,840
Until help arrives, I'm deputizing
the little guy, the skinny one,

433
00:34:34,920 --> 00:34:36,360
and the boy with
the patch on his eye

434
00:34:36,440 --> 00:34:37,760
to come with me in
the station wagon.

435
00:34:37,840 --> 00:34:40,920
Randy, you drop in and head up
river with the rest of your troops,

436
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:42,240
split up on foot.

437
00:34:42,320 --> 00:34:44,400
Becky, call Jed,
tell him to circle over

438
00:34:44,480 --> 00:34:46,920
this end of the island
and fly low.

439
00:34:59,360 --> 00:35:00,440
Is it them?

440
00:35:00,520 --> 00:35:01,560
Yeah, yeah.

441
00:35:02,720 --> 00:35:04,000
They found the campfire.

442
00:35:04,080 --> 00:35:08,920
Rats! I should have put
more pine needles on it. Let's go.

443
00:35:15,200 --> 00:35:16,480
Be careful.

444
00:35:47,480 --> 00:35:49,080
What do you creeps want?

445
00:35:49,880 --> 00:35:51,280
We're looking for you.

446
00:35:52,240 --> 00:35:53,360
Why?

447
00:35:53,960 --> 00:35:55,320
Well, because
you're a fugitive.

448
00:35:55,400 --> 00:35:57,640
No, I'm not.
I quit the Khaki Scouts.

449
00:35:57,720 --> 00:36:00,160
Well, it doesn't matter
anyway. You don't have that authority.

450
00:36:00,240 --> 00:36:01,520
We've been deputized.

451
00:36:01,600 --> 00:36:04,840
Now, you're going to come
along peacefully or not?

452
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:09,280
Listen to some reason.

453
00:36:09,360 --> 00:36:11,440
I don't like you.
You don't like me.

454
00:36:11,520 --> 00:36:14,200
So, why don't you
just let us disappear?

455
00:36:15,160 --> 00:36:18,080
Well, it's tempting,
but we can't allow it.

456
00:36:19,200 --> 00:36:20,480
You know,
you shouldn't be friends with him.

457
00:36:21,320 --> 00:36:22,360
Why not?

458
00:36:23,080 --> 00:36:24,240
Because he's crazy.

459
00:36:25,480 --> 00:36:27,120
Maybe you just don't know him.

460
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:30,360
Actually, we know him
a lot better than you.

461
00:36:30,440 --> 00:36:32,360
He's emotionally disturbed
because his family died.

462
00:36:32,440 --> 00:36:34,160
Nickleby, tie him up.

463
00:36:37,640 --> 00:36:43,040
Do not cross this stick.

464
00:36:50,840 --> 00:36:52,320
You're doomed, Shakusky.

465
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:31,320
Molly's right, I do go berserk.

466
00:37:33,640 --> 00:37:35,280
It was him or us.

467
00:37:39,800 --> 00:37:40,960
Oh, no.

468
00:37:45,760 --> 00:37:47,920
She stabbed
Redford in the back with lefty scissors.

469
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:49,680
Repeat that, please? Over.

470
00:37:49,760 --> 00:37:52,920
Puncture wound, lower lumbar.
Make room for a stretcher in the cockpit.

471
00:37:53,320 --> 00:37:54,520
You're going to be okay.

472
00:37:54,640 --> 00:37:57,560
Thank goodness she
missed the artery. Here, bite on this.

473
00:37:57,640 --> 00:37:59,480
I tried to chop him,
but he dodged my tomahawk.

474
00:37:59,560 --> 00:38:01,040
He's got
excellent marksmanship.

475
00:38:01,160 --> 00:38:02,360
Shot Deluca in both arms.

476
00:38:02,440 --> 00:38:04,720
I guess we're going to miss
the Hullabaloo after all.

477
00:38:04,800 --> 00:38:06,120
Where's Snoopy?

478
00:38:07,400 --> 00:38:09,400
Those sons of bitches.

479
00:38:09,480 --> 00:38:12,080
They got him right
through the neck.

480
00:38:14,040 --> 00:38:15,720
Was he a good dog?

481
00:38:17,200 --> 00:38:21,400
Who's to say.
But he didn't deserve to die.

482
00:38:37,480 --> 00:38:38,600
What happened? Who is that?

483
00:38:38,680 --> 00:38:39,760
Clear the dock, Edgar!

484
00:38:39,840 --> 00:38:41,400
- Why is he bleeding?
- Is Suzy with you?

485
00:38:41,520 --> 00:38:43,200
No, she's in
the woods with Shakusky.

486
00:38:43,280 --> 00:38:44,320
Where am I going?

487
00:38:44,400 --> 00:38:47,320
The infirmary at Fort Lebanon.
We'll be right behind you. You got it?

488
00:38:47,400 --> 00:38:48,520
Yup.

489
00:38:48,600 --> 00:38:49,880
Warm up the motor,
I'll be right back.

490
00:38:49,960 --> 00:38:51,280
Hold it right there!

491
00:38:52,240 --> 00:38:53,400
You're not leaving this island.

492
00:38:53,520 --> 00:38:56,360
Our daughter has been
abducted by one of these beige lunatics.

493
00:38:56,440 --> 00:38:58,800
Walt, it's very clear.

494
00:38:58,880 --> 00:39:00,840
The two of them
conspired in this together.

495
00:39:00,920 --> 00:39:02,280
Don't worry,
Mr. Bishop. She'll be safe.

496
00:39:02,360 --> 00:39:03,640
Sam's got excellent
wilderness skills.

497
00:39:04,760 --> 00:39:06,760
Why can't you
control your Scouts?

498
00:39:08,600 --> 00:39:09,880
Well, I'm trying.

499
00:39:12,840 --> 00:39:13,960
Hey.

500
00:39:14,040 --> 00:39:15,120
Stop it! Stop it!

501
00:39:15,200 --> 00:39:16,800
- Stop it!
- Stop it.

502
00:39:16,880 --> 00:39:21,520
I do blame him.
But I also blame myself and both of you.

503
00:39:21,600 --> 00:39:26,080
With all due respect,
you can't let your children stab people.

504
00:39:26,160 --> 00:39:27,720
What are you talking about?

505
00:39:27,800 --> 00:39:29,400
